<h3>Disease burden of mental health and neurodevelopmental disorders</h3>
Health impacts are often measured in terms of total numbers of deaths. It has been strongly argued that such metrics significantly underestimate the impact of mental health disorders for two reasons.[ref]Prince, M., Patel, V., Saxena, S., Maj, M., Maselko, J., Phillips, M. R., &amp; Rahman, A. (2007). No health without mental health.Â <i>The Lancet</i>,Â <i>370</i>(9590), 859-877. Available <a href="http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(07)61238-0/fulltext">online</a>.[/ref] The first is that from the perspective of mortality, direct deaths typically only result from alcohol, drug use and eating disorders. However, suicide deaths are also strongly linkedÂ â€” although not always attributed toÂ â€” mental health disorders. We discuss the evidence of this link between mental health and suicide <a href="https://ourworldindata.org/mental-health/#link-between-mental-health-and-suicide">later in this entry</a>. It is nonetheless recognised that a given share of suicide deaths are attributed to this group of disorders; including this proportion of suicides would significantly increase the total attributed number of deaths.

It is also true that the metric of mortality fails to capture the true health and wellbeing costs of mental health disorders. In the charts below we present data on the attributed '<a href="https://ourworldindata.org/burden-of-disease">disease burden</a>' (measured in Disability-Adjusted Life Years; DALYs). This metric considers not only death rates, but also years lived with disability or health burden. As a share of total disease burden, mental health and neurodevelopmental disorders typically account for 7-10 percent, but up to 13 percent in some countries.

